Package constraints

Package containing classes used as constraints for command line arguments

See: Description

  • Interface Summary 
    Interface Description
    ArgumentConstraint<E>
    Basic interface for all argument constraints
    ByteConstraint
    Basic interface for all byte constraints
    DoubleConstraint
    Basic interface for all double constraints
    FloatConstraint
    Basic interface for all float constraints
    IntegerConstraint
    Basic interface for all integer constraints
    LongConstraint
    Basic interface for all long constraints
    ShortConstraint
    Basic interface for all short constrains
    StringConstraint
    Basic interface for all string constrains
  • Class Summary 
    Class Description
    AllowedSetConstraint<T>
    This constraint is used to specify a list of allowed elements, from which the given argument have to be later selected.
    EmptyArgumentConstraint
    This class represent constraint which is fulfilled when the argument value is empty
    LowerBoundConstraint<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
    This class represent a constraint which is fulfilled when the argument value is higher or equal than the specified lower bound
    RangeConstraint<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
    This class represent a constraint which is fulfilled when the argument value is between the lower and upper bound, including both boundary values
    StringLengthConstraint
    This class represent a constraint which is fulfilled when the string's length is between the minimal and maximal bound, including both boundary values
    StringMaxLengthConstraint
    This class represent a constraint which is fulfilled when the string's length is higher than or at least the same as the minimal bound
    StringMinLengthConstraint
    This class represent a constraint which is fulfilled when the string's length is higher than or at least the same as the minimal bound
    UpperBoundConstraint<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
    This class represent a constraint which is fulfilled when the argument value is lower or equal than the specified upper bound
